Piezoelectric Energy Generator for Toll Gate Applications

A sustainable energy harvesting system designed to convert mechanical pressure from moving vehicles into usable electrical energy using the piezoelectric effect. This project focuses on integrating piezoelectric transducers beneath toll gate speed breakers or humps to generate renewable electricity from everyday vehicular movement.

As vehicles pass over the embedded piezoelectric sensors, the mechanical stress produced by the vehicle weight is converted into electrical energy. The generated output is processed through a rectifier and voltage regulation circuit, then stored in rechargeable batteries or capacitors for powering low-energy applications such as LED lighting, roadside sensors, display systems, and smart toll infrastructure.

The system demonstrates an innovative approach toward green energy generation by utilizing otherwise wasted mechanical energy from traffic movement. By combining renewable energy harvesting with transportation infrastructure, the project promotes eco-friendly and energy-efficient smart road systems.

Key Features
- Converts vehicular pressure into electrical energy
- Uses piezoelectric transducers embedded in road humps
- AC to DC conversion using rectifier circuits
- Energy storage using rechargeable batteries
- Suitable for powering LEDs, sensors, and toll gate electronics
- Low-maintenance and environmentally friendly design
- Scalable for highways, parking areas, and smart city applications
Technologies & Components Used
- Piezoelectric Sensors (PZT/PVDF)
- Bridge Rectifier Circuit
- Voltage Regulator
- Energy Storage Unit
- LED Load System
- Mechanical Hump Structure
- Power Conditioning Circuit

Working Principle

When a vehicle moves over the specially designed hump, pressure is applied to the piezoelectric materials placed beneath it. This mechanical stress generates an alternating electrical signal due to the direct piezoelectric effect. The generated AC voltage is converted into DC using a bridge rectifier, regulated for stability, and stored in batteries or capacitors for later use.

